SIMPLE: observer
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Observer
<hw>Ob*serv"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who
observes, or pays attention to, anything; especially, one engaged in, or
trained to habits of, close and exact observation; <as>as, an
astronomical <ex>observer</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The observed of all <qex>observers</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Careful <qex>observers</qex> may foretell the hour,⟦br⟧
By sure prognostic, when to dread a shower.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who keeps any law, custom, regulation, rite,
etc.; one who conforms to anything in practice.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Diligent
<xex>observers</xex> of old customs.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These . . . hearkened unto <qex>observers</qex> of times.</q>
<rj><qau>Deut. xviii. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who fulfills or performs; <as>as, an
<ex>observer</ex> of his promises</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A sycophantic follower.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Observership</ent>⟦br⟧
